A plot from the tibble

The spread of GDP within the continents, as shown by plotting the mean GDP value for each country

Figure 1. The spread of GDP within the continents, as shown by plotting the mean GDP value for each country

What this figure/table show

Table 1 shows the spread of GDP within each continent. In addition to the mean, minimum and maximum values of GDP for each country, the difference between the minimum and maximum GDP has also been calculated. This can be used to identify countries where there is greater economic inequality, i.e. the difference between min and max GDP is greater. Figure 1 shows the spread of GDP within each continent by plotting the means of GDP per country. The most notable feature of this figure is the larger spread of GDP in Asia and Europe compared to Africa and the Americas.

Task option 6 - A country with an interesting story

A tibble

A few preliminary data exploration steps were taken to identify a country with an interesting story

  1. Plot all countries GDP per capita over time
(ggplot(gapminder, aes(year, gdpPercap)) + geom_jitter()) #To quickly explore the dataframe. There are some clear outliers here

  1. From the above graph, there are clearly some countries that are outliers, so to identify which country they represented I made the following tibble:
gapminder %>% 
    filter(gdpPercap > 75000) #Kuwait has the highest GDP per capita from 1952-1972, but happens after?
## # A tibble: 5 x 6
##   country continent  year lifeExp    pop gdpPercap
##   <fct>   <fct>     <int>   <dbl>  <int>     <dbl>
## 1 Kuwait  Asia       1952    55.6 160000   108382.
## 2 Kuwait  Asia       1957    58.0 212846   113523.
## 3 Kuwait  Asia       1962    60.5 358266    95458.
## 4 Kuwait  Asia       1967    64.6 575003    80895.
## 5 Kuwait  Asia       1972    67.7 841934   109348.
  1. After identifying Kuwait as the outlier in the data, I filtered the gapminder dataframe down to the following tibble:
(Kuwait <- gapminder %>%
  filter(country == "Kuwait") %>%
  select(-"lifeExp"))

A plot from the tibble

Figure 3. GDP per capita over and population change over time in Kuwait

What this figure/table show

Table 3 shows population and GDP per capita over time for Kuwait. In preliminary data exploration, Kuwait was an outlier in global GDP per capita values when plotted over time, hence why it was chosen to be a country with an interesting story. GDP per capita for Kuwait was expectionally higher than other countries, especially from 1952-1972. Figure 3 goes on to plot the change in GDP per capita over time, which is characterised by large drop between 1972 and 1982. Over time population, which is indicated by colour, is increasing, following a general trend of decreasing GDP per capita, however this also follows a global trend of population increase over time.
